</arg></template></paragraph><paragraph>The<space/><bold>Brassicales</bold><space/>are an<space/><link><target>order (biology)</target><part>order</part></link><space/>of<space/><link><target>flowering plant</target><trail>s</trail></link>, belonging to the<space/><link><target>eurosids II</target></link><space/>group of<space/><link><target>dicotyledon</target><trail>s</trail></link><space/>under the<space/><link><target>APG II</target></link><space/>system.<extension extension_name='ref'><template><target>cite journal</target><arg name="author">[[Angiosperm Phylogeny Group]]<space/></arg><arg name="year">2003<space/></arg><arg name="title">An update of the Angiosperm Phylogeny Group classification for the orders and families of flowering plants: APG II<space/></arg><arg name="journal">[[Botanical Journal of the Linnean Society]]<space/></arg><arg name="volume">141<space/></arg><arg name="issue">4<space/></arg><arg name="pages">399–436<space/></arg><arg name="doi">10.1046/j.1095-8339.2003.t01-1-00158.x</arg></template></extension><space/>One character common to many members of the order is the production of<space/><link><target>glucosinolate</target></link><space/>(mustard oil) compounds. Most systems of classification have included this order, although sometimes under the name<space/><bold>Capparales</bold><space/>(the name chosen depending on which is thought to have priority).<extension extension_name='ref' name="hall2002"><template><target>cite journal</target><arg name="author">Jocelyn C. Hall, Kenneth J. Sytsma & Hugh H. Iltis<space/></arg><arg name="year">2002<space/></arg><arg name="title">Phylogeny of Capparaceae and Brassicaceae based on chloroplast sequence data<space/></arg><arg name="journal">[[American Journal of Botany]]<space/></arg><arg name="volume">89<space/></arg><arg name="issue">11<space/></arg><arg name="pages">1826–1842<space/></arg><arg name="pmid">21665611<space/></arg><arg name="doi">10.3732/ajb.89.11.1826</arg></template></extension></paragraph><paragraph>The order typically contains the following families:<extension extension_name='ref' name="Haston"><template><target>cite journal</target><arg name="author">Elspeth Haston, James E. Richardson, Peter F. Stevens, Mark W. Chase & David J. Harris<space/></arg><arg name="year">2007<space/></arg><arg name="title">A linear sequence of Angiosperm Phylogeny Group II families<space/></arg><arg name="journal">[[Taxon (journal)|Taxon]]<space/></arg><arg name="volume">56<space/></arg><arg name="issue">1<space/></arg><arg name="pages">7–12<space/></arg><arg name="url">http://www.ingentaconnect.com/content/iapt/tax/2007/00000056/00000001/art00002</arg></template></extension></paragraph><list type='bullet'><listitem><link><target>Akaniaceae</target></link></listitem><listitem><link><target>Bataceae</target></link><space/>salt-tolerant shrubs from America and<space/><link><target>Australasia</target></link></listitem><listitem><link><target>Brassicaceae</target></link><space/><link><target>Mustard plant</target><part>mustard</part></link><space/>and<space/><link><target>cabbage</target></link><space/>family; may include the<space/><link><target>Cleomaceae</target></link></listitem><listitem><link><target>Capparaceae</target></link><space/><link><target>caper</target></link><space/>family, sometimes included in<space/><link><target>Brassicaceae</target></link></listitem><listitem><link><target>Caricaceae</target></link><space/><link><target>papaya</target></link><space/>family</listitem><listitem><link><target>Cleomaceae</target></link><extension extension_name='ref' name="APGIII2009"></extension></listitem><listitem><link><target>Gyrostemonaceae</target></link></listitem><listitem><link><target>Koeberliniaceae</target></link></listitem><listitem><link><target>Limnanthaceae</target></link><space/><link><target>meadowfoam</target></link><space/>family</listitem><listitem><link><target>Moringa</target><trail>ceae</trail></link><space/>thirteen species of trees from Africa and India</listitem><listitem><link><target>Pentadiplandraceae</target></link></listitem><listitem><link><target>Resedaceae</target></link><space/><link><target>Mignonette (Reseda)</target><part>mignonette</part></link><space/>family</listitem><listitem><link><target>Salvadoraceae</target></link></listitem><listitem><link><target>Setchellanthaceae</target></link></listitem><listitem><link><target>Tovariaceae</target></link></listitem><listitem><link><target>Tropaeolaceae</target></link><space/><link><target>Tropaeolum</target><part>nasturtium</part></link><space/>family</listitem></list><paragraph>Under the<space/><link><target>Cronquist system</target></link>, the Brassicales were called the Capparales, and included among the &quot;<link><target>Dilleniidae</target></link>&quot;. The only families included were the<space/><link><target>Brassicaceae</target></link><space/>and<space/><link><target>Capparaceae</target></link><space/>(treated as separate families), the<space/><link><target>Tovariaceae</target></link>,<space/><link><target>Resedaceae</target></link>, and<space/><link><target>Moringaceae</target></link>. Other taxa now included here were placed in various orders.</paragraph><paragraph><link><target>File:Cleome (Spider Flower) in Gavi.jpg</target><part>thumb</part><part>upright</part><part>''<link><target>Cleome hassleriana</target></link>''</part></link></paragraph><paragraph>The families Capparaceae and Brassicaceae are closely related. One group, consisting of<space/><italics><link><target>Cleome</target></link></italics><space/>and related genera, was traditionally included in the Capparaceae but doing so results in a<space/><link><target>paraphyletic</target></link><space/>Capparaceae.<extension extension_name='ref' name="hall2002"></extension><space/>Therefore, this group is generally now either included in the Brassicaceae or as its own family,<space/><link><target>Cleomaceae</target></link>.<extension extension_name='ref' name="Haston"></extension><extension extension_name='ref'><template><target>cite journal</target><arg name="author">Jocelyn C. Hall, Hugh H. Iltis & Kenneth J. Sytsma<space/></arg><arg name="year">2004<space/></arg><arg name="title">Molecular phylogenetics of core Brassicales, placement of orphan genera ''Emblingia'', ''Forchhammeria'', ''Tirania'', and character evolution<space/></arg><arg name="journal">[[Systematic Botany]]<space/></arg><arg name="volume">29<space/></arg><arg name="pages">654–669<space/></arg><arg name="doi">10.1600/0363644041744491<space/></arg><arg name="url">http://www.botany.wisc.edu/sytsma/LabWeb/pdf/Hall2004.pdf<space/></arg><arg name="format">[[Portable Document Format|PDF]]</arg></template></extension></paragraph><heading level='2'>References</heading><paragraph><template><target>reflist</target><arg>32em</arg></template></paragraph><heading level='2'>External links</heading><list type='bullet'><listitem><template><target>Commons category-inline</target><arg>Brassicales</arg></template></listitem></list><paragraph><link><target>Category:Brassicales</target><part></part></link><link><target>Category:Angiosperm orders</target></link></paragraph><paragraph><template><target>Brassicales-stub</target></template></paragraph></article>